I have a good-nice condition (for these Swiss rifles) Swiss K31 ( K-31 ) that has been dated to 1946. The post-WWII K31's (1946 and on...) are some of the better mechanical K31's due to defects being worked out after years of K31 production, and lack of firing due to WWII being over.

The bore is nice and shiny, sharp groves. The stock and especially the buttstock has the normal snow and military drilling wear one see's on K-31's. The Swiss were just tough on their stocks, but not abusive. That said, the stock is solid and no cracks as most K31's are.

Also has the troop tag. All numbers match on gun. The troop tag reflects the person in Switzerland that was issued this gun and kept it at his house. Swiss requirement.

K31's are the the most accurate WWII rifles as well as the Swedish Mauser. Look it up if you don't believe me. These guns shoot MOA and ballistics\recoil similar to a 308. The steel used is top notch and to produce one of these today would be $2,000 as I have read.  All precision as Swiss stuff is noted for.  And OMG, the 2-stage trigger is absolutely crisp with about a 3-3.5 break. Sadly, better trigger than on some on my more expensive and modern rifles.

Be an awesome whitetail gun for the upcoming season, from swamps to 300 yards. I mean, when was the last time you shot a deer with a genuine WWII weapon..or a bolt action rifle with open sights...? Fun challenge and bragging rights at deer camp.

Straight pull bolt action. Very fun to use! And ammo is easy to find. For example, Prvi Partisan is good stuff, easy to find, and sells for anywhere from $15-18 a box. http://www.sgammo.com/product/prvi-partizan/20-round-box-75x55-swiss-174-grain-fmj-prvi-partizan-ammo-pp721

GP11 Swiss ammo is usually $300 for a case of 480 rounds and that ammo is match quality.

Priced to sell at $320, especially with the sling, troop tag, and case.

FTF only, do not want to ship at this time.

NO TRADES PLEASE and please dont ask. Hate to sell, but need car repairs that came up.

Thanks.

---------

Here is a good writeup of the K31's and its predecessor, the K-11.

http://www.iraqveteran8888.com/the-iv8888-blog/the-k31-swiss-service-rifle



"Accuracy:

The K31 is likely one of the finest military rifles ever produced. Much care and detail when into their manufacture, and since they were not under the duress of war, they were able to take their time and build them right. This equates to an extremely accurate and top notch firearm. The steel used by the Swiss is very high quality with a high nickel content. Barrels are extremely well made and I have never shot one that did not group at least 1.5" at 100 yards with GP11 ammunition. The triggers are very well thought out two stage arrangements with a nice clean 3-4 pound break. Sights are typical tangent sights that would have been found on most rifles of the era, and are adjustable for windage and elevation. The accuracy of the K31 is often attributed to Adolf Hitler's refusal to invade the Swiss during WW2. Probably the best decision he ever made, as they were all heavily trained to be expert marksmen."


Kimber, Winchester, Remington, Sako, Weatherby, Savage, Howa, Marlin, Browning, Mauser, SKS, AK

The Sig Sauer P238 is different from most other .380 “pocket” pistols on the market today. In terms of size and shape, the P238 is very similar to other comparable micro .380’s. Instead of a polymer frame, however, the Sig Sauer P238 uses an all metal frame with a single action design, and is almost identical in appearance to the legendary Colt Mustang.The Sig Sauer P238 operates with a locked-breech short recoil action. The hammer must be cocked either manually, or by the action of the slide, to fire each shot. The advantage to this method of operation is two- fold. First and foremost, similar to the Colt 1911 or Mustang, the Sig Sauer P238 has a superior trigger pull when compared to similarly sized double action only designs like the Ruger LCP, Smith & Wesson Bodyguard or Kel-Tec P3AT. In turn, this leads to greater accuracy. Second, the P238’s single action design allows Sig Sauer to incorporate a high ride beavertail grip frame, which leads to greater control under recoil by safely placing the shooter’s hand higher along the bore axis.In addition to being a great-looking pistol, the Sig Sauer P238 is much easier to load than other micro pistols on the market. For shooters that do not possess strong hands, the P238’s smooth and easy slide is one of its most highly appreciated features. There are also positive vertical serrations on the back of the slide that further enhance loading or unloading.The Sig Sauer P238 slide locks to the rear on an empty magazine, and the slide latch release is easy to reach with the thumb of the shooting hand. Similarly, the P238 has a user friendly manual thumb safety which further enhances shooter usability. The Sig Sauer P238 has stippling on the grips for a secure hold while firing the pistol. As mentioned, the frame has a generous beavertail to protect the web between the shooter’s thumb and trigger finger, and the hammer recesses into the beavertail section, to avoid any chance of hammer or slide-bite while firing the pistol. The Sig Sauer P238 is a very compact design, and while it may be slightly heavier than the polymer .380ACP pistols on the market, it is just as small. The LCP utilizes a double-action only, hammer-fired mechanism, with the hammer recessed into the rear of the slide to prevent snagging. The double-action only firing mode makes it simple to use in stressed situations—no levers or switches to remember—just point and shoot. The LCP features low profile front and rear sights integrated onto the slide that do not snag on clothing when pistol is drawn from a concealed position, and all sharp edges have been eliminated on the LCP to aid in concealment and to reduce wear on clothing. Right-handed shooters can comfortably reach the magazine release on the LCP with their thumb, while left-handed shooters have no problem using their trigger finger. Unlike many small semi-automatic pistols that operate with a blowback action, the Ruger LCP operates on a locked-breech system, which mitigates recoil and does not necessitate the user to pull the slide back against an excessively heavy recoil spring during loading. The LCP also has a manual slide hold-open latch for inspection and cleaning.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Original Import - 90/91 Jericho 941 in 9mm. $350 OBO
postcontent:
I have an original Jericho 941 in 9mm for sale. It has a slide mounted safety, IWI, KBI Inc, and H-3 markings as well as a Serial Number of 01017X (I can sent a picture of the full SN to serious buyers). This is not one of the new ones... this one was imported in 90/91. It is a quality and historical pistol that hasn't been made in over 20 years. 

The Jericho 941 is a steel pistol designed for the Israeli military and police. After being imported by IWI industries for a few years the Israelis sent the design to Magnum Research and changed the name to the "Baby Desert Eagle" after changing the design. I wish I could keep it forever, but I don't go pistol shooting that often and it's time to move it to a new home.

I am asking $350 for this pistol (OBO). I've been looking for almost a year, and I cannot find anyone else selling an original. The new ones are okay, but they lack the historyIts steel body and SA/DA hammer helps keep the sights on target for accurate follow up shots.

The only problem with this pistol is the Safety. If you use the slide release to send the slide forward instead of slignshoting it the Safety may turn off. The internet says this can be fixed with a single part from a CZ pistol, but I don't have the time or emotional investment to fix it. It's still shootable, just not safe for carry in its current shape.

Don't give up your chance to get this historical pistol. It will be a long time before you see another one for sale... if you ever do. One of the reasons they are so rare is this pistol was featured in Cowboy Bebop, a famous Japanese comic. Its fans snatch these originals up really quickly.
